  url = {https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780123749840003211},
  urldate = {2023-05-24},
  abstract = {The term ‘conjugation’ is used in genetics to describe two general types of systems of genetic exchange. One involves normally haploid bacteria with the ability to transfer DNA to other bacterial cells or in some cases to plants. The process can lead to acquisition of new genes and/or to partial diploidy (merodiploidy). The genes encoding the conjugational machinery may be carried on plasmid or chromosomal replicons. A replicon can be mobilized by conjugational machinery encoded by a different replicon. The most common type of machinery required involves similar functional steps in widely divergent bacterial taxa. Recipient cells may exclude or modulate transfer. The second kind of conjugation involves diploid protozoan ciliates such as Paramecium, which can exchange entire haploid nuclei between cells.},
